            'description' => '<p><b>Critias</b> (<span></span>; Greek: <span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek language text">Κριτίας</span>, <i>Kritias</i>; c. 460 – 403 BCE) was an ancient Athenian political figure and author.  Born in Athens, Critias was the son of Callaeschrus and a first cousin of Plato\'s mother Perictione. He became a leading and violent member of the Thirty Tyrants. He also was an associate of Socrates, a fact that did not endear Socrates to the Athenian public.
</p><p>Critias was noted in his day for his tragedies, elegies and prose works. Some, like Sextus Empiricus, believe that Critias wrote the <i>Sisyphus fragment</i>; others, however, attribute it to Euripides. His only known play is <i>Peirithous,</i> of which only a single 42-line fragment survives (Sextus Empir. p. 403, 1). In addition, eight shorter quotations from unidentified plays have come down to us.
</p>


',
