            'description' => '<p><b>Albertus Magnus</b>, O.P. (c. 1193 – November 15, 1280), also known as <b>Saint Albert the Great</b> and <b>Albert of Cologne</b>, was a German Catholic Dominican friar and bishop. Later canonised as a Catholic saint, he was known during his lifetime as <i>Doctor universalis</i> and <i>Doctor expertus</i> and, late in his life, the sobriquet <i>Magnus</i> was appended to his name. Scholars such as James A. Weisheipl and Joachim R. Söder have referred to him as the greatest German philosopher and theologian of the Middle Ages. The Catholic Church distinguishes him as one of the 36 Doctors of the Church.
