                'intro' => 'Italian writer, philosopher, politician',
            'description' => '<p><b>Benedetto Croce</b> (<span></span>; <small>Italian: </small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[beneˈdetto ˈkroːtʃe]</span>; 25 February 1866 – 20 November 1952) was an Italian idealist philosopher, historian and politician, who wrote on numerous topics, including philosophy, history, historiography and aesthetics. In most regards, Croce was a liberal, although he opposed <i>laissez-faire</i> free trade and had considerable influence on other Italian intellectuals, including both Marxist Antonio Gramsci and fascist Giovanni Gentile. Croce was President of PEN International, the worldwide writers\' association, from 1949 until 1952. He was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Literature sixteen times.</p>',
