<p><b>John Ralston Saul</b>,  (born June 19, 1947) is a Canadian writer, political philosopher, and public intellectual. Saul is most widely known for his writings on the nature of individualism, citizenship and the public good; the failures of manager-led societies; the confusion between leadership and managerialism; military strategy, in particular irregular warfare; the role of freedom of speech and culture; and critiques of the modern economic situation. He is a champion of freedom of expression and was the International President of PEN International, an association of writers. Saul is the co-founder and co-chair of the Institute for Canadian Citizenship, a national charity promoting the inclusion of new citizens.
</p><p>His work is known for being thought-provoking and ahead of its time, leading him to be called a "prophet" by  <i>Time</i> and to be included in <i>Utne Reader\'</i>s list of the world\'s leading thinkers and visionaries. His works have been translated into 25 languages in 36 countries.</p>',
