                'description' => '<p><b>Liú Ān</b> (Chinese: <span lang="zh-Hant">劉安</span>, c. 179–122 BC) was a Han dynasty Chinese prince and an advisor to his nephew, Emperor Wu of Han (武帝). He is best known for editing the (139 BC) <i>Huainanzi</i> compendium of Daoist, Confucianist, Buddhist and Legalist teachings. Early texts represent Liu An in three ways: the "author-editor of a respected philosophical symposium", the "bumbling rebel who took his life to avoid arrest", and the successful Daoist adept who transformed into a <i>xian</i> and "rose into the air to escape prosecution for trumped-up charges of treason and flew to eternal life."</p>',
