                'description' => '<p><b>Jizang</b> (Chinese: <span lang="zh">吉藏</span>; pinyin: <i><span lang="zh-Latn-pinyin">Jízàng</span></i>; Wade–Giles: <i><span lang="zh-Latn-wadegile">Chi-tsang</span></i>. Japanese: 吉蔵<span> (<span lang="ja">kichizō</span>)</span>) (549–623) was a Persian-Chinese Buddhist monk and scholar who is often regarded as the founder of East Asian Mādhyamaka. He is also known as Jiaxiang or Master Jiaxiang (Chinese: <span lang="zh-Hant">嘉祥</span>; Wade–Giles: <i><span lang="zh-Latn-wadegile">chia hsiang</span></i>) because he acquired fame at the Jiaxiang Temple.
