                'description' => '<p><b>Asaṅga</b> (Tibetan: <span lang="bo">ཐོགས་མེད།</span>, Wylie: <i>thogs med</i>, traditional Chinese: <span lang="zh-Hant" title="Chinese language text">無著</span>; ; pinyin: <i>Wúzhuó</i>; Romaji: <i>Mujaku</i>) (fl. 4th century C.E.) was a major exponent of the Yogacara tradition in India, also called <i>Vijñānavāda</i>. Traditionally, he and his half-brother Vasubandhu are regarded as the founders of this school. The two half-brothers were also major exponents of Abhidharma teachings.
