                'description' => '<p><b>Udyotakara</b> (or <b>Uddyotakara</b>) (c. 6th century CE) was a philosopher of the Nyaya school of Indian philosophy. <i>Subandhu</i>’s <i lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit transliteration"><i>Vāsavadattā</i></i> mentioned him as the rescuer of the <i>Nyaya</i>. He was a brahmin of <i>Bharadvaja</i> gotra and he belonged to the Pashupata sect. His philosophical treatise, the <i><i lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit transliteration">Nyāyavārttika</i></i> was written to defend Vatsyayana\'s  <i><i lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit transliteration">Nyāyavāṣya</i></i> against the criticisms made by Dignaga.</p>',
