                'description' => '<p><b>Chandrakirti</b> (IAST: <i><i lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit transliteration">Candrakīrti</i></i>; traditional Chinese: <span lang="zh-Hant" title="Chinese language text">月稱</span>; pinyin: <i>Yuèchēng</i>; Japanese: <i lang="ja" title="Japanese language text">Gesshō</i>; Tibetan: <span lang="bo">ཟླ་བ་གྲགས་པ་</span>, Wylie: <i>zla ba grags pa</i>, Lhasa dialect IPA: <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">tàwa ʈʰàʔpa</span>;  <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span> 600</span> – c.<span> 650</span>) was a Buddhist scholar of the Madhyamaka school and a noted commentator on the works of Nagarjuna (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span> 150</span> – c.<span> 250 CE</span>) and those of his main disciple, Aryadeva, authoring two influential works, <i>Prasannapadā</i> and <i>Madhyamakāvatāra</i>.</p><p>Very little is known about Chandrakirti\'s life. Tibetan sources state that he was born in Samanta, South India. and was a student of Kamalabuddhi. He is traditionally associated with Nalanda Mahavihara where he may have been a monk.</p>',
