<p><b>Vidyaranya</b> (IAST: Vidyāraṇya) is variously known as a kingmaker, patron saint and high priest to Harihara I and Bukka Raya I, the founders of the Vijayanagara Empire. He was the 12th Jagadguru of the Śringeri Śarada Pītham from 1380-1386.</p><p>Vidyaranya helped the brothers establish the empire sometime in 1336. He later served as a mentor and guide to three generations of kings who ruled over the Vijayanagara Empire. Vijayanagara (Hampi), the capital of the empire, had a temple dedicated to Mādhavācārya.
</p><p>He was also a reputed Sanskrit-language author. He is identified as <b>Madhavacharya</b>, the author of the <i><i lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit transliteration">Sarvadarśanasaṅgraha</i></i>, a compendium of different philosophical schools of Hindu philosophy and <i>Pañcadaśī</i>, an important text for Advaita Vedanta.
