            'description' => '<p><b>Kumazawa Banzan</b><span> (<span lang="ja">熊沢 蕃山</span>, 1619 – September 9, 1691)</span> was an adherent of a branch of Neo-Confucianism called Wang Yangming Studies (Japanese: <i>Yōmeigaku</i>: 陽明学), who lived during the early Edo period. His childhood name (yōmei) was  Sashichirō<span> (<span lang="ja">左七郞</span>)</span>, his imina was Hakukei<span> (<span lang="ja">伯継</span>)</span>, also read Shigetsugu. His common name (azana) was Ryōkai<span> (<span lang="ja">either 了介 or 良介</span>)</span>, and he was commonly known by the personal names (tsūshō) as Jirōhachi<span> (<span lang="ja">次郎八</span>)</span> or Suke\'emon<span> (<span lang="ja">助右衛門</span>)</span>. His most common courtesy name (gō) was Sokuyūken<span> (<span lang="ja">息游軒</span>)</span>. His surname "Kumazawa" (熊沢) was changed to that of "Shigeyama" (蕃山) in 1660 and the latter, read in Sino-Japanese as "Banzan", became his posthumous courtesy title, by which even now he is commonly known.
