                'intro' => 'American philosopher',
            'description' => '<p><b>Kelly Oliver</b> (born 1958) is an American philosopher specializing in feminism, political philosophy and ethics. She is W. Alton Jones Professor of Philosophy at Vanderbilt University in Nashville, Tennessee. She is also a founder of the feminist philosophy journal <i>philoSOPHIA</i>.</p><p>Oliver is the author of 15 scholarly books, six edited volumes, and dozens of scholarly articles. Her books include <i>Carceral Humanitarianism: The Logic of Refugee Detention</i> (2017), <i>Hunting Girls: Sexual Violence from The Hunger Games to Campus Rape</i> (2016), and <i>Earth and World: Philosophy After the Apollo Missions</i> (2015). She is also a novelist and the author of <i>The Jessica James Mysteries</i>, which include <i>Wolf</i>, <i>Coyote</i>, and <i>Fox</i>.</p>',
