            'intro' => 'Italian-French author',
            'description' => '<p class="mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<p><b>Christine de Pizan</b> (also seen as <b>de Pisan</b>; <small>French pronunciation: </small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[kʁistin də pizɑ̃]</span><small class="nowrap"> (<span><span><span> </span>listen</span></span>)</small> ; 1364 – c. 1430) was an Italian author. She is best remembered for defending women in <i>The Book of the City of Ladies</i> and <i>The Treasure of the City of Ladies</i>. Pizan was a prominent moralist and political thinker in medieval France. Pizan\'s patrons included Louis of Orleans, Philip the Bold and John the Fearless. She served as a court writer during the reign of Charles VI. Her books of advice to princesses, princes and knights remained in print until the 16th century.
</p><p>In recent decades, Pizan\'s work has been returned to prominence by the efforts of scholars such as Charity Cannon Willard, Earl Jeffrey Richards and Simone de Beauvoir.
</p>',
